04187nam a22005295i 9780822397007DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19971997ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223970077 a10.1515/97808223970072doi  a(DE-B1597)554480  a(OCoLC)1229160743  a(OCoLC)1226679124  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a810.9/8971 aWalker, Cheryl, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIndian Nation :bNative American Literature and Nineteenth-Century Nationalisms /cCheryl Walker. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1997] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b6 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Americanists00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- t1. The Subject of America: The Outsider Inside -- t2. Writing Indians -- t3. The Irony and Mimicry of William Apess -- t4. Black Hawk and the Moral Force of Transposition -- t5. The Terms of George Copway's Surrender -- t6. John Rollin Ridge and the Law -- t7. Sarah Winnemucca's Mediations: Gender, Race, and Nation -- t8. Personifying America: Apess's "Eulogy on King Philip" -- t9. Native American Literature and Nineteenth-Century Nationalisms -- tAppendix: "The Red Man's Rebuke" -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIndian Nation documents the contributions of Native Americans to the notion of American nationhood and to concepts of American identity at a crucial, defining time in U.S. history. Departing from previous scholarship, Cheryl Walker turns the "usual" questions on their heads, asking not how whites experienced indigenous peoples, but how Native Americans envisioned the United States as a nation. This project unfolds a narrative of participatory resistance in which Indians themselves sought to transform the discourse of nationhood.Walker examines the rhetoric and writings of nineteenth-century Native Americans, including William Apess, Black Hawk, George Copway, John Rollin Ridge, and Sarah Winnemucca. Demonstrating with unique detail how these authors worked to transform venerable myths and icons of American identity, Indian Nation chronicles Native American participation in the forming of an American nationalism in both published texts and speeches that were delivered throughout the United States. Pottawattomie Chief Simon Pokagon's "The Red Man's Rebuke," an important document of Indian oratory, is published here in its entirety for the first time since 1893.By looking at this writing through the lens of the best theoretical work on nationality, postcoloniality, and the subaltern, Walker creates a new and encompassing picture of the relationship between Native Americans and whites. She shows that, contrary to previous studies, America in the nineteenth century was intercultural in significant ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822397007zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822397007423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822397007.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles